name: Introduction to Computer Science
description: This course offers a thorough introduction to computer science focusing on problem solving program development and algorithmic thinking in Java including sorting searching data structures and recursion.

name: Data Structures
description: The course delves into the crucial aspects of data structures and algorithms for their operation employs these structures to enhance algorithm design and broadens knowledge in searching sorting and hashing techniques.

name: Introduction to Discrete Structures I
description: This course introduces students to the mathematical tools of logic and induction basic concepts of relations functions and sets as foundational knowledge for further computer science studies emphasizing inductive definitions and proofs for solving computer science problems.

name: Introduction to Discrete Structures II
description: The course offers foundational knowledge in combinatorics and probability theory essential for algorithm design and analysis system analysis and other computer science areas.

name: Computer Architecture
description: The course addresses key aspects of modern computer system design including the creation and implementation of essential hardware components like processors memory and I/O devices and the interaction between software and hardware.

name: Design and Analysis of Computer Algorithms
description: The course focuses on studying various practical algorithms analyzing their complexity to derive insights into principles and data structures valuable in algorithm design.

name: Calculus I for Math & Physical Sciences
description: Math 151 delves into differential calculus of single-variable elementary functions including rational trigonometric and exponential functions and their inverses explores applications through the Mean Value Theorem and introduces integral calculus.

name: Calculus II for Math & Physical Sciences
description: Math 152 explores integral calculus and its applications infinite series and power series theory parametric curves polar coordinates and complex numbers.

name: Intro to Linear Algebra
description: The topics cover vectors in n-space systems of linear equations Gaussian elimination span and linear independence of vectors matrix algebra determinants subspaces basis and dimension eigenvalues and eigenvectors matrix diagonalization vector geometry projections orthogonal vectors symmetric matrices and their applications

name: Data management for Data Science
description: The course in the SAS Data Science Certificate program teaches students to acquire curate and explore real-world data using Python and databases focusing on efficient data management and basic analysis with SQL and NoSQL suitable for all majors without extensive programming requirements.

name: Software Methodology
description: The course focuses on Java software development covering object-oriented design UML testing GUI programming version control with CVS using Eclipse basics of mobile development multithreading network programming and object persistence.

name: Systems Programming
description: This course focuses on low-level programming and system administration tasks covering topics such as memory management and process control

name: Principles of Programming Languages
description: Principles of Programming Languages explores various programming paradigms and language design concepts offering insight into the theory behind programming languages

name: Numerical Analysis and Computing
description: Numerical Analysis and Computing introduces students to algorithms for solving mathematical problems on computers emphasizing numerical stability and efficiency

name: Numerical Methods
description: Numerical Methods focuses on techniques for approximating solutions to mathematical problems including root finding interpolation and numerical integration

name: Introduction to Imaging and Multimedia

name: General Physics I
description: This course offers an elementary yet detailed analysis of fundamental physics topics including motion; gravitation; momentum; energy; electromagnetism; waves; heat; kinetic theory; quantum effects; and atomic and nuclear structure.

name: General Physics II
description: Building upon the concepts introduced in General Physics I; this course continues the exploration of fundamental physics principles; covering topics such as electromagnetism; waves; heat; kinetic theory; quantum effects; and atomic and nuclear structure in more depth.

name: General Physics Lab
description: Complementary to the theoretical aspects covered in General Physics I; this laboratory course provides hands-on experiments and practical applications related to motion; gravitation; momentum; energy; electromagnetism; waves; heat; and atomic and nuclear structure.

name: General Physics Lab II
description: This laboratory course complements the concepts covered in General Physics II; offering students further practical experience in conducting experiments related to electromagnetism; waves; heat; quantum effects; and atomic and nuclear structure.

name: Anal Physics I
description: Analytic Physics I delves into the mathematical frameworks governing motion; forces; energy; and properties of matter; providing students with a deeper understanding of fundamental physical principles.

name: Anal Physics I Lab
description: Complementing Anal Physics I; this lab course allows students to apply theoretical concepts from the lecture through hands-on experiments; reinforcing their understanding of analytical physics principles.

name: Anal Physics IIA
description: Building upon the foundational concepts introduced in Analytic Physics I; this course explores advanced topics in classical mechanics; electromagnetism; and thermodynamics; offering students a more comprehensive understanding of these subjects.

name: General Physics II Lab
description: Similar to its counterpart for General Physics I; this lab course provides students with practical experience and experimentation in topics related to electromagnetism; waves; heat; quantum effects; and atomic and nuclear structure.

name: Honors Physics I
description: This honors-level course delves into advanced topics such as relativity; wave and quantum properties of photons and electrons; atomic and molecular structures; nuclear physics; and elementary particles; offering a rigorous exploration of these concepts.

name: Honors Physics II
description: Continuing from Honors Physics I; this course further explores advanced physics topics including relativity; wave and quantum properties; atomic and molecular structures; nuclear physics; and elementary particles; providing a deeper understanding of these complex phenomena.

name: Classical Physics Laboratory
description: This laboratory course complements the theoretical aspects covered in Honors Physics I and II; offering students the opportunity to conduct experiments related to relativity; wave and quantum properties; atomic and molecular structures; nuclear physics; and elementary particles.

name: Classical Physics Laboratory
description: This laboratory course complements the theoretical aspects covered in Honors Physics I and II; offering students the opportunity to conduct experiments related to relativity; wave and quantum properties; atomic and molecular structures; nuclear physics; and elementary particles.

name: Extended General Physics
description: Similar to General Physics I and II but with a broader scope; this course provides an elementary yet detailed analysis of fundamental physics topics; catering to students who require additional instruction or have a broader interest in physics.

name: Extended General Physics II
description: A continuation of Extended General Physics; this course further expands on fundamental physics principles; offering students a comprehensive understanding of various topics in physics.

name: Physics for the Sciences
description: Introduction to physics with biological ecological and chemical applications Selected topics in mechanics thermodynamics fluids waves electricity magnetism optics and modern physics Integrated laboratory experiments

name: Physics for the Sciences II
description: Building upon the concepts introduced in Physics for the Sciences I; this course continues to explore physics principles with applications in biological ecological and chemical contexts; further expanding on topics such as mechanics thermodynamics fluids waves electricity magnetism optics and modern physics.

name: General Chemistry for Engineers
description: This course provides a foundational understanding of chemistry tailored for engineering students; covering principles such as stoichiometry atomic and molecular structure thermodynamics equilibrium kinetics and nuclear chemistry.

name: General Chemistry
description: A comprehensive introduction to chemical principles and their applications; covering topics such as stoichiometry states of matter atomic and molecular structure solutions thermodynamics equilibrium oxidation-reduction kinetics nonmetals metals coordination compounds and nuclear chemistry.

name: General Chemistry II
description: Building upon the concepts introduced in General Chemistry I; this course explores more advanced topics such as chemical equilibrium kinetics electrochemistry and other principles; providing students with a deeper understanding of chemical phenomena.

name: General Chemistry III
description: Continuing from General Chemistry II; this course further expands on chemical principles and their applications; covering topics such as thermodynamics equilibrium kinetics and other advanced concepts in chemistry.

name: Honors Gen Chem
description: Focusing on fundamental chemical principles including stoichiometry atomic structure and thermodynamics; this honors-level course offers a rigorous exploration of introductory chemistry concepts.

name: Honors Gen Chem II
description: Building upon the concepts introduced in Honors Gen Chem I; this course delves deeper into topics such as chemical equilibrium kinetics and electrochemistry; providing students with a comprehensive understanding of these principles.

name: Gen Chem Lab
description: Complementing the theoretical aspects covered in general chemistry courses; this laboratory course offers hands-on experiments illustrating basic chemical methods and principles.
